,"Shanid, Limerick, Ireland":"County Limerick, Ireland","Castle Shanid,Connello,Limerick,Ireland":"Limerick, County Limerick, Ireland","Huntspill,Bridgwater,Somerset,England":"Huntspill, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Marisco","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Nicola, Canio, Dante, Dario, Domenic, Giacinto, Gino, Guido, Italo, Marcello, Romolo.","Italian (southern): topographic name from the Salentine dialect word <i>marascu</i> ‘mullein’ (from Latin <i>verbascum</i>)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Geoffrey","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Germanic (Frankish and Lombard) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It was in regular use among the counts of Anjou, ancestors of the English royal house of Plantagenet, who were descended from Geoffrey Plantagenet, Count of Anjou (  1113–51 ). It was a particularly popular name in England and France in the later Middle Ages; notable bearers in England include the poet  Geoffrey Chaucer  (  <i>c.</i>1340–1400 ) and in Wales the chronicler  Geoffrey  of Monmouth (  d. 1155 ). The original form and meaning of the name is disputed. According to one theory, it is merely a variant of   Godfrey ;  others derive the first part from the Germanic word <i>gawia</i> ‘territory’, <i>walah</i> ‘stranger’, or <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’. Medieval forms can be found to support all these theories, and it is possible that several names have fallen together, or that the name was subjected to reanalysis by folk etymology at an early date."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1355923,"age":37,"year":"1167","julianDay":2147298,"description":"Arrival of Normans at Baginbun in Co. Wexford thus started 800 year struggle between English and Irish.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Geoffrey de Marisco was born in 1130, in Huntspill, Somerset, England, United Kingdom, his father, Robert de Marisco, was 30 and his mother, Lucy d'Alneto, was 20. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Geoffrey de Marisco. He died in 1179, in Limerick, County Limerick, Ireland, at the age of 49."},"et":{"1130–1179":"1130–1179","1110–1165":"1110–1165","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1155–1213":"1155–1213","1170–1245":"1170–1245","1100–1139":"1100–1139","1110–Female":"1110–Surnud","1139":"1139","1213":"1213","1179":"1179","1245":"1245","1167":"1167","1100":"1100","1155":"1155","1165":"1165","1110":"1110","1130":"1130","about 1155":"umbes 1155","1170":"1170","Castle, Limerick, Ireland":"County Limerick, Iirimaa","Lucca, Toscana, Italy":"Lucca, Toscana, Itaalia","Shanid, Limerick, Ireland":"County Limerick, Iirimaa","Castle Shanid,Connello,Limerick,Ireland":"Limerick, County Limerick, Iirimaa","Huntspill,Bridgwater,Somerset,England":"Huntspill, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1130–1179":"1130–1179","1110–1165":"1110–1165","–Male":"Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1155–1213":"1155–1213","1170–1245":"1170–1245","1100–1139":"1100–1139","1110–Female":"1110–Kuollut","1139":"1139","1213":"1213","1179":"1179","1245":"1245","1167":"1167","1100":"1100","1155":"1155","1165":"1165","1110":"1110","1130"